<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,1928,2021]" lastBlockId="7.[151,1436,151,1008]" lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="58" pageId="6" pageNumber="57">
Abdomen. Tergite I covered with dark brown scales and white scales laterally; tergites II–VII covered with dark brown scales, yellow scales forming thin stripes on posterior margins (
<figureCitation box="[1000,1067,1963,1987]" captionStart="FIGURES 7 – 12" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1984,2007]" captionTargetBox="[159,1426,347,1923]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,337,1963]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 7 – 12. Toxophora paulistana: (7) General habitus, lateral view; (8) Abdomen, dorsal view; (9) Epandrium, dorsal view; (10) Male terminalia, with epandrium removed, lateral view; (11) Spermathecae; (12) Furca." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/278781/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="57">
Fig. 
<number box="[1052,1067,1963,1987]" pageId="6" pageNumber="57" value="8.0">8</number>
</figureCitation>
); sternites I–IV with dark brown scales and white scales on posterior margin; sternites IV–VII with dark brown scales and yellow scales on posterior margin. Terminalia with posterior margin of epandrium concave (
<figureCitation box="[881,949,151,175]" captionStart="FIGURES 7 – 12" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1984,2007]" captionTargetBox="[159,1426,347,1923]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,337,1963]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 7 – 12. Toxophora paulistana: (7) General habitus, lateral view; (8) Abdomen, dorsal view; (9) Epandrium, dorsal view; (10) Male terminalia, with epandrium removed, lateral view; (11) Spermathecae; (12) Furca." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/278781/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="58">
Fig. 
<number box="[933,949,151,175]" pageId="7" pageNumber="58" value="9.0">9</number>
</figureCitation>
), with a small projection on center, fused to posterodorsal region of gonocoxite; cercus with a group of small dark-brown setae forming circular spot; hypandrium absent; gonocoxites ventrally fused, without median internal ridge; distiphallus shorter than epiphallus, wide and with broad apex; epiphallus with long base and apex wide with two long projections on lateroventral faces (
<figureCitation box="[159,244,290,314]" captionStart="FIGURES 7 – 12" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1984,2007]" captionTargetBox="[159,1426,347,1923]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,337,1963]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 7 – 12. Toxophora paulistana: (7) General habitus, lateral view; (8) Abdomen, dorsal view; (9) Epandrium, dorsal view; (10) Male terminalia, with epandrium removed, lateral view; (11) Spermathecae; (12) Furca." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/278781/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="58">
Fig. 
<number box="[213,244,290,314]" pageId="7" pageNumber="58" value="10.0">10</number>
</figureCitation>
); gonostylus short with thin and pointed apex; lateral aedeagal apodemes and ejaculatory apodeme short, both not surpassing gonocoxal limits.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,151,1008]" pageId="7" pageNumber="58">
Female. Similar to male, except for: dichoptic; lack of setae on femur III; tibia I and II with a row of setae on posterior surface; furca with two parallel rods and a central piece with an anterior spine, all connected by membranous tissue (
<figureCitation box="[290,373,429,453]" captionStart="FIGURES 7 – 12" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1984,2007]" captionTargetBox="[159,1426,347,1923]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,337,1963]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 7 – 12. Toxophora paulistana: (7) General habitus, lateral view; (8) Abdomen, dorsal view; (9) Epandrium, dorsal view; (10) Male terminalia, with epandrium removed, lateral view; (11) Spermathecae; (12) Furca." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/278781/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="58">
Fig. 
<number box="[342,373,429,453]" pageId="7" pageNumber="58" value="12.0">12</number>
</figureCitation>
). Spermathecae with spermathecal bulbs sclerotized, tubular and strongly coiled; spermathecal ducts 1.5 times longer than sperm pump; sperm pump with well developed sclerotized collars with indented margins (
<figureCitation box="[213,294,498,522]" captionStart="FIGURES 7 – 12" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1984,2007]" captionTargetBox="[159,1426,347,1923]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,337,1963]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 7 – 12. Toxophora paulistana: (7) General habitus, lateral view; (8) Abdomen, dorsal view; (9) Epandrium, dorsal view; (10) Male terminalia, with epandrium removed, lateral view; (11) Spermathecae; (12) Furca." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/278781/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="58">
Fig. 
<number box="[265,294,498,522]" pageId="7" pageNumber="58" value="11.0">11</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="58" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,151,1008]" pageId="7" pageNumber="58">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,533,557]" pageId="7" pageNumber="58">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet refers to a person or thing native to São Paulo city, 
<collectingCountry box="[1140,1211,533,557]" name="Brazil" pageId="7" pageNumber="58">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, type-locality of the new species, and is treated as a noun in apposition.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="58" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,151,1008]" box="[199,792,602,627]" pageId="7" pageNumber="58">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,352,602,627]" pageId="7" pageNumber="58">Distribution.</emphasis>
<collectingCountry box="[359,428,602,626]" name="Brazil" pageId="7" pageNumber="58">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(São Paulo and Santa Catarina).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,151,1008]" pageId="7" pageNumber="58">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,409,637,662]" pageId="7" pageNumber="58">Taxonomic notes.</emphasis>
The examination of non-identified specimens of 
<taxonomicName box="[978,1098,637,661]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Toxophora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="58" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[978,1098,637,661]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="58">Toxophora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
housed at 
<collectionCode box="[1226,1310,638,661]" pageId="7" pageNumber="58">BMNH</collectionCode>
revealed a population from Mato Grosso (
<collectingCountry box="[510,581,671,695]" name="Brazil" pageId="7" pageNumber="58">Brazil</collectingCountry>
) which fits perfectly with the redescription of 
<taxonomicName authority="Macquart" authorityName="Macquart" box="[1124,1436,672,696]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Toxophora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="58" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aurea">
<emphasis box="[1124,1319,672,696]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="58">Toxophora aurea</emphasis>
Macquart
</taxonomicName>
presented by 
<bibRefCitation box="[301,522,706,731]" pageId="7" pageNumber="58" refString="Cunha, A. M., Lamas, C. J. E. &amp; Couri, M. S. (2009) Redescription of two neotropical species of Toxophora Meigen (Diptera, Bombyliidae, Toxophorinae). Papeis Avulsos de Zoologia, 49, 18, 221 - 227." type="journal article">
<collectingCountry box="[301,374,706,730]" name="Saint Helena, Ascension and Tristan da Cunha" pageId="7" pageNumber="58">Cunha</collectingCountry>
<emphasis box="[381,430,707,731]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="58">et al</emphasis>
. (
<number box="[453,514,706,730]" pageId="7" pageNumber="58" value="2009.0">2009</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
, except for the presence of a inter-radial vein (
<figureCitation box="[1045,1129,706,730]" captionStart="FIGURES 13 – 24" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1682,1705]" captionTargetBox="[202,1366,197,1662]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[193,1376,193,1671]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 13 – 24. (13) Toxophora amphitea Walker, 1849, wing; (14) Toxophora vasta Coquillett, 1891, wing, IR: inter-radial crossvein; (15) Toxophora leucon Séguy, 1930, wing; (16) Toxophora aurea Macquart, 1848, wing; (17) Toxophora varipennis Williston, 1901, wing; (18) Toxophora virgata Osten Sacken, 1877, abdomen, dorsal view; (19) Toxophora aurea Macquart, 1848, abdomen, dorsal view; (20) Toxophora zikani d’Andretta &amp; Carrera, 1950, abdomen, dorsal view; (21) Toxophora travassosi d’Andretta &amp; Carrera, 1950, abdomen, dorsal view; (22) Toxophora zikani d’Andretta &amp; Carrera, 1950, scape, dorsal view; (23) Toxophora aurea Macquart, 1848, posterior margin of thorax, dorsal view; (24) Toxophora amphitea Walker, 1849, thorax, lateral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/278782/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="58">
Fig. 
<number box="[1098,1129,706,730]" pageId="7" pageNumber="58" value="14.0">14</number>
</figureCitation>
), which is not found in this species (
<figureCitation box="[247,329,741,765]" captionStart="FIGURES 13 – 24" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1682,1705]" captionTargetBox="[202,1366,197,1662]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[193,1376,193,1671]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 13 – 24. (13) Toxophora amphitea Walker, 1849, wing; (14) Toxophora vasta Coquillett, 1891, wing, IR: inter-radial crossvein; (15) Toxophora leucon Séguy, 1930, wing; (16) Toxophora aurea Macquart, 1848, wing; (17) Toxophora varipennis Williston, 1901, wing; (18) Toxophora virgata Osten Sacken, 1877, abdomen, dorsal view; (19) Toxophora aurea Macquart, 1848, abdomen, dorsal view; (20) Toxophora zikani d’Andretta &amp; Carrera, 1950, abdomen, dorsal view; (21) Toxophora travassosi d’Andretta &amp; Carrera, 1950, abdomen, dorsal view; (22) Toxophora zikani d’Andretta &amp; Carrera, 1950, scape, dorsal view; (23) Toxophora aurea Macquart, 1848, posterior margin of thorax, dorsal view; (24) Toxophora amphitea Walker, 1849, thorax, lateral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/278782/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="58">
Fig. 
<number box="[298,329,741,765]" pageId="7" pageNumber="58" value="16.0">16</number>
</figureCitation>
). Dissections of both male and female terminalia of specimens from this population were made that reinforced the hypothesis of conspecificity. Based on this, we believe that this character, alone, is not strong enough to support the description of a new species and we considered it as morphological intraspecific variation of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Toxophora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="58" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aurea">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="58">T. aurea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
